There is no idle declamation against heredi- tary honors; but the blindness of men belonging· to an exclusive class, whose claime to distinction were founded upon the marite of the grem and good of former generations and unsupportedby any personal merite of their own, is shown in language to which no one can object and reasoning which admits of no answer. The Satire is in the form of aletter addressed to one Pontius. Heis one of the class against whose degenerare members the Satire Is directed; and we may sup- pose he was a young man with what we should call good prospecte. The pride of birth and the degeneracy of inherited nobility were not new features of society in Juvenal’s time, and they have not grown so old in ours but that generations to come will complain-as he did, and pour contempt, aa he did not, on the inheritance of noble names, however virtuous their possessore maybe.
